This paper focuses on the analysis of argumentative conversations using a novel neural model, which suggests that it is likely to fall under the category of natural language processing (NLP) and computational linguistics (CL), which is represented by cs.CL. The use of a neural model also suggests that it could fall under the category of artificial intelligence (AI), which is represented by cs.AI. The study also involves the analysis of social media conversations, which suggests that it could fall under the category of social and information networks (SI), which is represented by cs.SI. The use of machine learning techniques to track dynamic patterns in argumentation processes suggests that it could fall under the category of machine learning (LG), which is represented by cs.LG. Finally, the study involves the analysis of discourse, which suggests that it could fall under the category of cybernetics (CY), which is represented by cs.CY.
